in psychological as well as in material terms. Individual chapters explore historical disasters and their commemoration, but others also consider of the effect of anticipated and imagined catastrophes. They analyze the destruction of cities both as a threat to be forestalled, and as a potentially regenerative agent of change, and the ways in which destroyed cities are revisited — and in a sense, rebuilt— in literary and social memory. The contributors to this volume seek to explore the Roman conception of disaster in terms that are not exclusively literary or historical. Instead, they explore the connections between and among various elements in the assemblage of experiences, texts, and traditions touching upon the theme of urban disasters in the Roman world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aKulturelles Gedächtnis. 4aLateinische Literatur. 4aRömische Geschichte. 4aStadt /Katastrophe. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aCultural Memory.  aLatin Literature.  aRoman History.  aUrban Disaster.1 aBromberg, Jacques A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, Honora Howell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Jessica H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCloss, Virginia M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCloss, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrell, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoseph, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeitel, Elizabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKraus, C. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKöster, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4ht